defs.text: OpenChain Provides Context For Situations involving Suppliers

text.tspan: A company puts out a call for tender to various suppliers.
This call for tender includes a provision allowing or explicitly
requesting for open source components to be used in the
solution proposed.
Two supplier companies offer proposals including open source
components.
One supplier is offering the open source components using an
non-OpenChain set of terms and open source compliance
measures.
The other supplier is offering the open source components using
the terms of the OpenChain industry standard.
A Simple Decision
The company’s procurement department is faced with
the choice of accommodating an unique approach to
receiving open source components or a best practices
methodology applied broadly in the market.
Relying on a tested and widely utilized industry
standard like OpenChain eases the process of
negotiation and facilitates trust in the appropriateness
of the methodology without an in-depth evaluation of an
individual supplier-specific approach and therefore
reduces risks and required time and efforts.
If non-compliance with open source requirements is
identified, the customer and supplier can work towards
a shared solution using the processes identified by the
OpenChain industry standard.
Furthermore, in any sequence of transactions involving
more than one company, the OpenChain industry
standard will additionally save time and resources.
The OpenChain Industry Standard in Action
Using the OpenChain industry standard in a typical sales and procurement workflow quickly
identifies which companies are aligned around industry-wide open source compliance best
practices and which companies are not.
